<article>

  <p>
    Sit down intending to be present, and watch what actually happens. Within seconds
    the mind has wandered into rehearsal, argument, or a half-formed plan — and for a
    stretch there is no recognition that wandering is what is occurring. The body is
    still. The eyes may be closed. Attention is elsewhere. That split is ordinary. It
    is also the condition the
    <span class="pali" data-pali="satipaṭṭhāna" data-en="foundations of mindfulness">Satipaṭṭhāna</span>
    <span class="pali" data-pali="sutta" data-en="discourse">Sutta</span>
    is built to interrupt.
  </p>

  <p>
    The English word <em>mindfulness</em> has come to cover almost anything attentive.
    Soft noticing. Stress reduction. A gentler commentary running alongside experience.
    MN 10 — and its longer sibling, DN 22 — uses a harder claim. This is
    <em>ekāyano ayaṃ maggo</em>: the one-way path, the direct path. Not a side skill.
    Not a warm-up for the real teaching. The four foundations are given for the
    purification of beings, for the ending of sorrow and grief, for the attainment of
    the true way, for the realisation of
    <a href="/concepts/nibbana/"><span class="pali" data-pali="nibbāna" data-en="liberation">nibbāna</span></a>.
    Calmer noticing without that aim is a different project wearing the same English word.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>Knowing, Not Narrating</h2>

  <p>
    <span class="pali" data-pali="sati" data-en="mindfulness">Sati</span>
    is often rendered "mindfulness," and the translation has done real work — and real
    damage. In this discourse the point is not a sharper inner monologue layered over
    sensation. It is contact with what is already appearing — including thoughts,
    known as thoughts rather than mistaken for the whole field. The enemy is not
    thought. It is the stretch of time when a narrative is running and there is no
    recognition that a narrative is what is occurring.
  </p>

  <p>
    A foundation —
    <span class="pali" data-pali="satipaṭṭhāna" data-en="foundations of mindfulness">satipaṭṭhāna</span>
    — is not a pedestal for a self to sit on. It is a domain where attention can stand
    without collapsing into the preferred narrative. The sutta does not ask anyone to
    invent a special inner life. It asks for accurate knowing of what is already
    occurring: body as body, feeling-tone as feeling-tone, mind as mind, phenomena as
    phenomena. That knowing is not cold detachment for its own sake. It is the
    condition under which clinging becomes visible — and, with enough clarity, less
    compulsive.
  </p>

  <p>
    The four domains are not four unrelated careers. They are successive apertures on
    the same stream. Breath practice as mapped in the
    <a href="/suttas/anapanasati/">Āṇāpānasati Sutta</a>
    can move through all four without changing objects.
    <span class="pali" data-pali="satipaṭṭhāna" data-en="foundations of mindfulness">Satipaṭṭhāna</span>
    names the map. Breath is one way of walking it.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>Where the Grip Tightens</h2>

  <p>
    The discourse works each foundation the same way: name the field, offer specific
    contemplations, then return to a refrain that never changes. The inventory matters
    less than the orientation. Still, each field catches clinging at a different joint.
  </p>

  <h3>Kāya — the body</h3>

  <p>
    Contemplation of
    <span class="pali" data-pali="kāya" data-en="body">kāya</span>
    begins where experience is hardest to fake: the living body. A
    <span class="pali" data-pali="bhikkhu" data-en="one on the path">bhikkhu</span>
    sits and knows a long breath as long, a short breath as short — clear knowing, not
    breath control. From there the field widens: postures; clear comprehension in
    ordinary activity; the body's parts; the four elements; the cemetery contemplations
    on decomposition.
  </p>

  <p>
    The sequence is not morbid theatre. It systematically dismantles the body's
    apparent solidity and permanence with the same clarity used on the breath. Body
    first, not because form is sacred, but because identification with it is thick —
    and because what can be known here is always available. Wanting and not-wanting
    trade places all afternoon; the body remains the ground they play on.
  </p>

  <h3>Vedanā — feeling-tone</h3>

  <p>
    The second foundation is
    <span class="pali" data-pali="vedanā" data-en="feeling-tone">vedanā</span>:
    the bare hedonic tone — pleasant, unpleasant, or neutral — that colors every moment.
    Worldly and spiritual feeling are distinguished; the instruction remains the same.
    Know pleasant as pleasant. Know unpleasant as unpleasant. Know neutral as neutral.
  </p>

  <p>
    Why this matters becomes clear in
    <a href="/concepts/paticca-samuppada/"><span class="pali" data-pali="paṭicca-samuppāda" data-en="dependent origination">dependent origination</span></a>.
    From feeling, craving tends to arise. Establishing
    <span class="pali" data-pali="sati" data-en="mindfulness">sati</span>
    on
    <span class="pali" data-pali="vedanā" data-en="feeling-tone">vedanā</span>
    means catching the tone before the reactive machinery of wanting and not-wanting
    fully engages. That is not suppression. It is seeing in the gap between contact and
    the story that usually follows — where a sit either opens or collapses
    back into unreflective habit.
  </p>

  <h3>Citta — the mind's weather</h3>

  <p>
    The third foundation turns to
    <span class="pali" data-pali="citta" data-en="mind">citta</span>
    — mind as the quality of awareness in this moment. A mind with lust is known as
    with lust; without lust, as without. Hatred and its absence; delusion and clarity;
    contraction and scatter; developed and undeveloped; unified and not; liberated and
    not. The list is empirical. These are tones that can be observed now.
  </p>

  <p>
    The instruction is not, first, to renovate the climate. It is to know it accurately.
    A mind clouded by anger that knows itself as clouded has already opened a slight
    gap between the state and identification with the state. Unreflective mind does not
    have that gap. Moods shift when attention stops feeding the story that sustains
    them — but the first move is recognition, not performance.
  </p>

  <h3>Dhammā — phenomena</h3>

  <p>
    The fourth foundation is the most expansive:
    <span class="pali" data-pali="dhamma" data-en="phenomena">dhammā</span>
    as phenomena — mental objects and teaching categories encountered as live events.
    Here the practitioner contemplates the five
    <a href="/concepts/five-hindrances/"><span class="pali" data-pali="nīvaraṇa" data-en="hindrances">nīvaraṇas</span></a>
    — knowing each when present, when absent, and the conditions for arising,
    abandoning, and non-reappearance. Then the five
    <a href="/concepts/khandhas/"><span class="pali" data-pali="khandha" data-en="aggregates">khandhas</span></a>
    of clinging; the six sense bases and the fetters that arise dependent on them; the
    seven factors of awakening
    (<span class="pali" data-pali="bojjhaṅgā" data-en="factors of awakening">bojjhaṅgā</span>);
    and finally the four noble truths themselves.
  </p>

  <p>
    This is where doctrine stops being something one believes about experience and
    becomes something one can watch operating. The hindrances are not a theory of
    distraction. They are the distraction, known as such.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>The Refrain Does the Work</h2>

  <p>
    After each contemplation, the sutta repeats the same refrain — dozens of times,
    unchanged. The repetition is not ornamental padding. It names the quality of
    attention that all the specific exercises share:
  </p>

  <blockquote>
    "In this way, in regard to the body he abides contemplating the body internally,
    or he abides contemplating the body externally, or he abides contemplating the
    body both internally and externally. He abides contemplating the nature of arising
    in the body, or he abides contemplating the nature of passing away in the body,
    or he abides contemplating the nature of both arising and passing away in the body.
    Mindfulness that 'there is a body' is established in him to the extent necessary
    for bare knowledge and continuous mindfulness. And he abides independent, not
    clinging to anything in the world."
    <cite>— MN 10 (adapted)</cite>
  </blockquote>

  <p>
    Three moves run through it. First, internal and external:
    <span class="pali" data-pali="sati" data-en="mindfulness">sati</span>
    is not only private introspection. One attends to this body, then to body as such,
    then to both — so practice does not collapse into self-absorption. Second, arising
    and passing:
    <span class="pali" data-pali="anicca" data-en="impermanence">anicca</span>
    is not a conclusion saved for the end of the sit. It is what attention is trained
    to see throughout. Third, the closing orientation: not clinging to anything in the
    world.
  </p>

  <p>
    That last line is easy to skip past. It is the direction of the whole map. The
    contemplations are not techniques for becoming more comfortable inside experience.
    They are a systematic loosening of the grip.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>What Soft Mindfulness Leaves Out</h2>

  <p>
    No other Pali text has shaped modern meditation culture quite like this one — and
    that influence has often flattened it. In many presentations,
    <span class="pali" data-pali="satipaṭṭhāna" data-en="foundations of mindfulness">Satipaṭṭhāna</span>
    becomes a chart of bare attention: present-moment awareness as a neutral skill, as
    useful for stress reduction as for liberation. The sutta itself is not neutral.
  </p>

  <p>
    It is anchored, throughout, in
    <span class="pali" data-pali="anicca" data-en="impermanence">anicca</span>,
    <span class="pali" data-pali="dukkha" data-en="unsatisfactoriness">dukkha</span>,
    and
    <span class="pali" data-pali="anattā" data-en="non-self">anattā</span>
    — the
    <a href="/concepts/ti-lakkhana/">three characteristics</a>.
    Seeing body as body,
    <span class="pali" data-pali="vedanā" data-en="feeling-tone">vedanā</span>
    as vedanā, mind as mind, is not equanimity as a lifestyle goal. It is the
    recognition that none of what is seen is stable, finally satisfying, or a permanent
    owner of experience. The refrain says the aim out loud: not clinging to anything
    in the world.
  </p>

  <p>
    Of course the discourse closes with a strong promise. One who practices in this way
    for seven years — or seven months, or seven days — should expect either full
    awakening or, if a remainder of clinging remains, non-return. Worth holding as the
    texts state it, without turning the numbers into a progress chart. The claim still
    matters: the path this sutta maps is not endless busywork. There is, the Buddha
    says, a shore on the other side.
  </p>

  <p>
    What remains for attention is simpler than the inventory suggests, and harder than
    the wellness reading admits. Know what is occurring while it is occurring. See it
    arise and pass. Notice the reach to cling — and the possibility of not taking that
    reach as destiny. The map is already drawn. The work is walking it with enough
    honesty that unexamined thought loses some of its grip.
  </p>

</article>
